{"author":{"id":"8e1777f58c0cfe5478428be8f9fcbfe90d25e44689578335da8fc2246fe0915a"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1628324476,"nonce":"rd1bOuMjeCGQw8AS1zjs1C8H3jU=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOAW4Y0s41UuBY","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/3695#issuecomment-894623832"},"message":"@neoformit, as I understand it would help if we add an 'rds' datatype as well? And make it more clear to the user? We can do so. You just need to add a similar line as here: https://github.com/galaxyproject/galaxy/blob/dev/lib/galaxy/config/sample/datatypes_conf.xml.sample#L630 and create a new datatypes class that represents `rds` like https://github.com/galaxyproject/galaxy/blob/dev/lib/galaxy/datatypes/binary.py#L2305\n\nBut let me throw in here one thing that we should consider whenever we deal with rdata or rds. To my understanding (and please correct me if that is wrong) both datatypes are not \"secure\". Tools producing those datatypes are ok, as long as the use-case is downloading the file and mess around with it - we overall trust our tools. But tools **consuming** rdata/rds is a security concern. rdata/rds can contain arbitrary code afaik, its like `pickle` in the Python world, isn't it? This way a user could upload a specifically crafted rdata/rds object execute it on our servers and maybe delete data, execute other programs .","files":null}]}